This is Back to Black (@backtoblackcoffee), a great little cafe near the Rijksmuseum.  Whereas in most cities the terms are interchangeable, in Amsterdam, there's definitely a distinction between a â€œcoffee shopâ€ & a â€œcafe.â€ The importance of this distinction depends entirely on your mood, sense of adventure, & probationary status.  All Amsterdamers have stories of visitors naively announcing - â€œWhere are these weed shops? Let's toke some green!â€ Nobody sounds cool saying â€œtoke some green,â€ & itâ€™s in these situations when Amsterdamers are forced to flip the big kill-switch known as â€œProject De-escalation: Keep Uncle Steve Away From The Weed.â€ Step 1 involves a long bike ride followed by trips to brewery/tasting rooms like Borouwer'ij (@brouwerijtij) or Butcher's Tears. If you can sneak in a few rounds of bitterballen with the heavy beers, itâ€™s likely your charge will forget their boastful weed promises.  If Step 1 doesnâ€™t work, Step 2 suggests a visit to a mellow coffee shop & slyly ordering - â€œMag ik je zwakste weed? I have an idiot tourist who doesn't need anything stronger than hash cut with a ton of rolling tobacco.â€ Once in hand, take your visitor on a walk to smoke & see the city. Theyâ€™ll last 30-45 minutes before crashing back at the hotel/AirBnb/your extra bedroom. Easy peasy!  The worst situation is when the visitor stays energetic through the bike ride, dubbels, bitterballen, & your kind offer to order weed. If they say â€œIt's cool, dude. Iâ€™ve smoked a lot of weed, I know the score,â€ the only option is traditional Dutch directness. â€œNo, Uncle Steve, you don't know the score. In fact, the score has been hydroponically mutated to such levels that you're going to end up wobbling down Leidsestraat wearing a knit Amsterdam beanie and asking strangers for the â€˜Hanses Blinkers Hotel.â€™ I don't want to be on a cold bench listening to you repeatedly slur 'I might puke,' while my actual friends have normal evenings. But, hey, you get to go back to Rochester or Atlanta or Fort Worth & tell everyone about the time you were â€˜in Amsterdam looking for coffee and ended up at a coffee shop.â€™â€ Find the best coffee & coziest cafes in Amsterdam on Sightseen.

Worst WinecafÃ© is a little tucked away in the Barentszstraat near the Haarlemmersquare. They serve fine small dishes for yourself or to share. Their great wine selection is served with passion and know-how. We love it, but it is rare in Amsterdam... We started of with some bread (baked daily at Restaurant As), anchovies with broad beans and pecorino and a clean green salad with mustard dressing. A good start! Tasty and pure.  From the sausage (worst) department we ordered fennel sausage served with braised pepper and fennel and the chicken sausage which came with morels and creamy spinach. We loved the former, liked the latter.  The cosy atmosphere and relaxed setting is perfect for a after work evening or laid back weekend night. Our stroll on the Amsterdam Marine Land of the Dutch Navy lead us to the Scheepskameel. Well, to be honest, it was the other way round, because the rumors about this place were very positive. Entering the Scheepskameel you immediately recognize the style of its older sister Rijsel. Both restaurants are housed in historic buildings, the interior tuned to it. This building used to be an education center for Naval chefs. In a new restaurant you would expect a lot of training and learning going on, but the open kitchen seems to be an oasis of tranquillity and harmony. The menu hosts numerous small dishes with a focus on raw ingredients and not too much focus on minimalistic presentations. It is all about the taste and we think it's delicious! In the wine department the Scheepskameel has made the choice to only serve German wines. Daring, but surprisingly well done! The service is of the kind that we would like to see more in Amsterdam. Friendly, courteous, expert.  All in all: this is another go people! The neighbourfood cafe Bar Mick is in the middle of the upcoming Spaarndammerstraat. It opens at 9 for coffee and breakfast and serves different menus throughout the day. The dinner menu only has meat and vegetarian options. We ordered the bavette and veggie burger, but the waiter mentioned that the vegetarian burger was actually not that good and advised us the vegetarian ravioli. So we did.  The bavette was cut with the grain, so not as tender as this 20,50 â‚¬ costing larded piece of meat should be. The ravioli was well undercooked. Add up the waiter that folds up the laundry in the bar during service, literally reads up the daily specials from the chalk board behind us and we come to the conclusion that there are far better ways to spend your euros. We love La Stage. It has become one of our favorite intimate restaurants in Amsterdam. Great to impress a date with mouth watering dishes, perfect service and even greater wine and food pairings. This restaurant close to the Nieuwmarkt has applied their proof of a Michelin star in the kitchen and doesn't show it off on their front window. It is exemplary for the modesty of the two partnered owners. In working life they divided the jobs clearly: he is in white, she is in black. The whites surprise you with creative and beautiful balanced dishes served in 4- to 6-course a la carte menus, the blacks indulge you with wonderful wines served with passion and knowledge. An empty table is rare, so reservations are advised. All in all a great place to celebrate life! â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€” Food â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸ Service â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸ Ambiance â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸ â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€” #dinner #restaurant #lastage #restaurantlastage.nl #geldersekade #nieuwmarkt #amsterdamcentrum #mackerel #amsterdam #amsterdamrestaurants #amsterdamfood #food #proefwerk #foodstagram #theartofplating

Mimi Latteria Milanese is located on the long long Kerkstraat near the corner with the Nieuwe Spiegelstraat. It is inspired on the small grocery stores that popped up in the post-war 50â€™s in Milan selling farmers products and serving home cooked dishes. This inspiration is to be found in the menu solely, because in the ambiance you would expect an â€˜artisanâ€™ touch but it is very contemporary. The restaurant is Italian owned and staffed, something we appreciate and gives a little confidence in taste. The menu provides a cross-section of Italian cuisine. Bruschette, some soups, pastas, and classic mains like vitello tonnato, coteletta alla Milanese, some salads and last but not least dolce like TiramisÃ¹ and dark chocolate pie. We chose for the Millefoglie, made of bread, vegetable and tomato caponata and mozzarella. Now technically what was on our plate was mozzarella, but after smoking it for about 15 minutes, the taste becomes much more dominant and then it is called scamorza. Not something we particularly appreciate and where other dishes were on the menu with scamorza specifically named, this dish hadnâ€™t. So we asked for some mozzarella instead and were told that this was actually mozzarella, but then smoked. After a short discussion about clear communication and some waiting for the new dish, we got what we wanted. And it was more then tasty the way it was advertised. We also tried and liked some Italian sweets and coffee. â€”â€”â€” Food â­ï¸â­ï¸ï¸â­ï¸ Service â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸ Ambiance â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸ â€”â€”â€” MIMI Latteria Milanese Kerkstraat 148 020-7370239, reservationsÂ possible www.facebook.com/latteriamilanese/ Open: Mon-Sun 8.00-22.00 â€”â€”â€” #breakfast #coffee #lunch #dinner #kerkstraat #museumplein #amsterdamcentre #amsterdam #amsterdamrestaurants #amsterdamfood #food #proefwerk #instafood #foodstagram #restaurantreviewÂ #amsterdamreview â€”â€”â€” Follow AMSTERDAM RESTAURANTS for more reviews of your next to know favorites.Â  Tag the friend that you want to bring here.

The plan was to go Salsa Shop. People had been raving about it for some time. One look at the food though and Mr.G and I were both standing outside with a sad face. Through the pouring rain we ran all the way to Wagamama. To spice things up, and feel like I was trying out something new anyhow, I was brave and decided to try out a new dish. Usually, I go for Yasai Itame or Chicken Kare Lomen, but this time I took Chicken Raisukareeâ€“and wasn't disappointed at all. Wagamama delivers, baby! What you see on the plate is chicken stir-fried in a coconut and lime curry sauce with mangetout, peppers, red and spring onions served on sticky white rice and garnished with red chillies, coriander and lime. I am also in love with the space, and actually, I like this whole street nowadays. The restaurants are mainstream but they are all pretty pimped up. Great for a super easy dinner with friends before taking the party elsewhere. #dontbeasnob #spiceitup #ilike #chicken #raisukaree #asianfood #food #wagamama #amstelstraat #rembrandtplein #amsterdam #amsterdamdinner #amsterdameats #amsterdamfood

There's a burger under that egg! Amsterdam had THE BEST food and I'm a picky eater (getting better). I was walking to another place and passed this restaurant on my way and came back another day. I was sick coming from Iceland and had a wicked sore throat my first couple of days in Amsterdam. I got this delicious and huge burger with equally delicious and fresh fries. Every thing was seasoned and so so good. They had a tea which soothed my throat almost instantaneously as well with lemon ginger and honey. I left stuffed and took home a slice of chocolate pie which was also amazing. The decor of this place was super cute and service was great. Recommend 10/10 Betty Blue for anyone passing through Amsterdam.  #bettyblue #food #foodporn #foodie #eaaats #eeeeeats #instafood #amsterdamfood #burgers #eggs #sunnysideegg #fries #amsterdamlife #travel #holland #netherlands #amsterdam #tea #nederlands

Half of the Ohmykase team was in Amsterdam this past holiday weekend, and, of course, had to find at least one sushi meal while in the city. We settled on the Michelin-rated Yamazato, located at the Hotel Okura Amsterdam. We were immediately greeted by a friendly waitstaff and seated promptly at the sushi bar. The serenity of the hotel and restaurant itself almost made it feel as though we were transported back to Japan. In particular we liked how the sushi bar was virtually hidden from the main dining room to add a more intimate vibe between those dining at the bar and the two chefs. While we enjoyed the fish quality and the chef's preparation of nigiri, we did think that there was room for improvement with the taste and texture of the rice, as well as with certain ingredients which could use additional refinement to expand the flavors. We do acknowledge that it may be a bit unfair to compare this meal to ones we've had at both Michelin-rated and non Michelin-rated sushi counters in NYC (since the never ending competition in NYC can be a factor in having chefs constantly refine techniques), however,  Yamazato may be worth visiting if you're ever in the mood for a higher-end sushi meal in Amsterdam

De Pijp, an Amsterdam neighborhood found just south of the canal ring, translates into English as 'The Pipeâ€™ - an early reference to either the public prostitution or the shape of the neighborhood. Historians disagree.  For the last couple of years, an actual pipe, the Amsterdam metro, has been digging its way under De Pijp. Not surprisingly, building a subway in a city that's below sea level is kind of tricky and led to the misfortune which was the 'Great Heineken Debacle of 2014,' when the Heineken brewery fell into a giant sinkhole. Even without its top tourist destination and the constant fear of sudden, gaping pits, De Pijp has managed to evolve into a neighborhood that lifestyle bloggers describe as â€œtrendyâ€ and â€œalive.â€ On sunny afternoons, try Sarphatipark if you're inclined to pop the top and get some color. The Albert Cuyp Market (#albertcuypmarkt) is (supposedly) the â€œlargest daytime market in Europeâ€ and has a few interesting food stands, but you're better off heading to Pho 91 (@pho91amsterdam), Spaghetteria (@spaghetteria_pastabar), or The Butcher (@thebutcheramsterdam). (**TIP - Thereâ€™s also great Surinamese just off the market on Eerste van der Helststraat.) For shopping, thereâ€™s Charlie + Mary (@charlieplusmary), All The Luck In The Worldâ€¦ (@alltheluckintheworld), and several other boutiques on the same block of Gerard Doustraat. If you're working away from the office, Stadskantine has plenty of window seating and a good atmosphere. For coffee, Scandinavian Embassy (@scandinavianembassy) and CT Coffee & Coconuts (@coffeecoconuts) are good spots.  Find more suggestions for the best of De Pijp on Sightseen's Neighbourhood Collections.  Download #sightseenapp from the App Store. I went hunting in my boss' fridge during a late night shift yesterday. Found spinach, pumpkin, lentils, organic cherry tomatoes, salmon and eggs. And I created this finger licking good bowl of veggie awesomeness. Roasted the tomatoes - lentils and pumpkin in the oven with tamari, cumin, ras el hanout and cayenne. Scrambled the eggs with salmon and miso and layered it on top of some fresh spinach. And sprinkled some roasted pumpkinseeds on top. Kind of Moroccan -Japanese fusion thingy. Pretty good. It made me feel at home in an empty loft at 22pm. ğŸ…ğŸ³ğŸ† At the moment I'm enjoying a little pre-Easter twosomeparty in rural Tuitjehorn with my Sol-mate ğŸŒ cooking spicy curries, drinking Syrah #vinnaturel and learning about the healing powers of herbs and other green leafy creatures. Hmm feels good to be out of Amsterdam. I literally have more space in my body and mind.

#tbt to the best poffertjes in Amsterdam. These little Dutch babies are fluffy, sweet and perfect to pop in your mouth. They come with an assortment of different toppings (Nutella, jams, butter etc) but they were recommended to be eaten with butter and powered sugar. The best I've had are in Nieuwmarkt Square from a food stand. A must eat every time I'm in Amsterdam.

The Westerpark hosts several great places to go to for lunch, drinks or an easy dinner. Pacific Parc has gotten some severe nearby competition over the last years (e.g. Mossel & Gin, Brouwerij Troost, Wester Wijnfabriek). These places are run by young, enthusiastic, hospitality minded people. In our multiple visits, we unfortunately didn't get this vibe at Pacific Parc. But hey: the biggest pro is the terrace and the food is ok! The large salads we had were sufficient in size, tasty and fresh. Only the Pata Negra mentioned on the menu was replaced by the cheaper JamÃ³n Serrano.  Do we still come here? Uhm yes. We have a Fish and Chips revival in Amsterdam. ViscafÃ© De Gouden Hoek, close to the Westerpark, was the first offering mainly Fish and Chips from daily catches. We love the ambiance which is very stylish and strengthening the concept. Here is what they do menu wise: some classic startes like croquettes, oysters and crab, but the main focus is of course on fish and chips. You choose one of the daily catches and combine it with one of three crusts with accompanying sauce. Choose from the classic crust with remoulade, a panko-crust with piccalilli or tempura-crust with Japanese Sriracha. When you donâ€™t have enough at hand, daily catches ask for good communication between kitchen and service staff. Which in our case didn't go very well. We were surprised when two out of three dishes served had a totally different fish then the one we had ordered. And we had to find out ourselves. Ah what the heck, the taste was good. Service wasnâ€™t to stable though. Some get it, others donâ€™t. Do we recommend this place? Yup! We revisited our friends of RIJKS last week because we had something to celebrate. We were almost as satisfied as last time. The food was amazing! Surprising and inspiring dishes that combine the best of food heaven: mouth-watering taste, all different textures creating sensational mouthfeel, cooked to perfection and served in extraordinary ways. This time we sat on the terrace facing the Rijksmuseum in soft yellow raking light. Just like the illumination used by the famous 'Hollandse Meesters' inside. Now partly the weather was at the base of our less experience in service. It was terrace weather at 5, they had to move everything inside at 6 because of expected rain and started to set the tabes outside again at 7, what made service become a little chaotic. Also some of the service staff seemed a little out of tone in terms of behavior and clothing. One couldnâ€™t stand still and explained the impressive dishes like he was on some sort of narcotic, while another was afraid to make eye contact and therefore stared at his unpolished shoes. Not something to expect when you enjoy an evening at this beautiful restaurant. The sommelier however did a great job, smile on his face, great wine/food pairing and not afraid to react to a joke. Because RIJKS is still on our Amsterdam Favorites list, we hope they take some time to not only polish the shoes. The kitchen deserves it! If you want to visit the RIJKS at a special occasion: on the 21st of august from 11pm on the doors stay open until 3am and they serve nothing but chicken and magnums of wine. We love Natural Wines and this Saturday you can experience them yourself! Walk in from 4 till 5:30 pm for a wine tasting. Go to the link in our bio or visit daykitchen.nl for more info!  What are natural wines? Simply put they are the more hardcore version of organic/biological wines. Since even after the picking of the grapes nothing is added. And this results in some pretty spectacular wines that we can't wait for you to try!

Madam is the panorama bar and restaurant on the 20th floor of the newly developed @adam_toren. It is the square part, just beneath the observation desk (HELLO IM ADAM) and above the 19th floor revolving restaurant where they will serve 5- and 8-course dinners. Madam has a more brasserie style menu with classics like steak tartar, Caesar salad and rack of lamb.  Going up in a spectacular elevator and welcomed with a glass of Champagne, we were first overtaken by the VIEW! Words can't describe it properly, but maybe you can stay tuned on @amsterdamview and see for yourself.  Our sneak peak 4 course dinner started with smoked salmon followed by tom kha kai, supreme chicken and yes: there was still some room for a chocolate mousse. We loved it. Service and food are only in need of some fine tuning, but all is done from the heart.  We are curious what Moon is going to be like! The Breakfast Club has opened a new branch on the Haarlemmerplein, which is still underdeveloped in terms of bars, restaurants and especially terraces. Where the first Breakfast Club is known for serving breakfast all day, here you can also enjoy dinner. Breakfast and lunch during the weekend are packed here. We went for a salad of the new dinner menu and it was very quiet. Portion wise we were not fully satisfied, but the price and taste was right. We got a nice salad with cray fish, loads of those little guys actually. It could have had a serving of bread and a little more green salad. And a price adjustment from now 10 to let's say 12 euros would be fine for dinner! Service was ok. Friendly, helpful, but they were struggling a little bit with the new menu. Indonesia was a former Dutch colony & has left its mark in the Netherlands with its cuisine. There are many Indonesian restaurants in Amsterdam & we decided to try one just to see how authentic the food is. MAX was recommended by our hotel & we tried the Rijsttafel (Indonesian banquet). Many small Indonesian dishes are served together with rice for sharing. I'd say the dishes are somewhat authentic, though adapted to suit the locals' taste. For example, the curry dishes weren't spicy at all (at least not to the Indonesian standard) & the achar had cauliflowers & capsicum. #Rijsttafel #indonesianfood #foodinmymouth #foodphotography #ilovesharingfood #foodporn #foodforfoodies #foodspotting #fooddiary #sharefood #food #instafood #foodgasm #burpple #amsterdamfood #travel #travelphotography #wanderlust #traveling #travelgram #holiday #vacation #instatravel #amsterdam

These are made of veal - they can be made of beef. It's like a really thick (and tasty) gravy texture on the inside, with a crisp fried breadcrumb texture on the outside. We had a mustard sauce and two other mystery sauces (although I suspect the white one is just a bomb mayonnaise.) In any case Joe is a huge fan! I ordered them mostly because the name rocks, but ended up being happy with the order.  #bitterballen #honeymoon #sogood #delicious #europeantravel #amsterdam #netherlands #amsterdamfood #veal #mustard #mayonnaise #europeanfood #nomnomnom #travelfood

Our stroll on the Amsterdam Marine Land of the Dutch Navy lead us to the Scheepskameel. Well, to be honest, it was the other way round, because the rumors about this place were very positive. Entering the Scheepskameel you immediately recognize the style of its older sister Rijsel. Both restaurants are housed in historic buildings, the interior tuned to it. This building used to be an education center for Naval chefs. In a new restaurant you would expect a lot of training and learning going on, but the open kitchen seems to be an oasis of tranquillity and harmony. The menu hosts numerous small dishes with a focus on raw ingredients and not too much focus on minimalistic presentations. It is all about the taste and we think it's delicious! In the wine department the Scheepskameel has made the choice to only serve German wines. Daring, but surprisingly well done! The service is of the kind that we would like to see more in Amsterdam. Friendly, courteous, expert.  All in all: this is another go people! Restaurant Moon in A'dam Toren is open. And we like it. The revolving restaurants makes one round every hour and makes you ooooh and aaaah for the stunning views of Amsterdam. So if you have company that you hate, just take a seat and look outside. But we suggest to go with people you adore, because not only the views are great, the food is too. Jaimie and his team create beautiful and tasteful dishes served in a set 5 or 8 course dinner. They co-create it with a line up of renowned Dutch music artists of which Thomas Acda is the first. Service had some startup problems where after the main course we had seen the 10th waiter at our table. Felt like the service sections didn't move along with the tables. Taste Amsterdam - Amstelpark, 2nd - 5th June.  Last year we spent a sun-soaked day here, eating & drinking until we ran out of the taste currency 'florijnen'. It was great & I've been looking forward to this years ever since.  This is a gathering of Amsterdam's top restaurants offering a number of dishes each. Also, there are bars of every description; cocktail, G&T, beer, champagne, the lot!  Also cooking demonstrations, workshops & plenty to occupy the kids. The highlight for them last year was a huge ferris wheel ride... for me it was the glass of champagne you got with each ride! ğŸ‘ğŸ» There is also a 'Taste of Kids' area, great for pre-schoolers & older.  My tip would be to get there early to grab somewhere nice to lounge & set up camp. Also take lots of money as the florijnen tend to go pretty quickly! One of the most famous Grand Cafes in Amsterdam. I stumbled upon this place on our hunt for good food. The cozy interior with the beautiful art decor details made it feel like I just walked out of Dutch beauty right into modern Parisian romance. The salad beef carpaccio was definitely one of the best I've ever had served with a blend of pine nuts, Parmesan and pesto, and for someone who is always on the hunt for a good carpaccio, this definitely exceeded my expectations. With truffle in abundance, I couldn't resist a meal here! Definitely a tick on the list for all the things my tummy loves!  For those who DM'd me about my previous food post about price points, this was comparatively  affordable taking into consideration the quality of service, food & ambience.  #theragtradeeats #theragtradetravels . . . . . . . #foodie #food #foodgasm #eatingfortheinsta #foodbloggers #lifestyle #travel #amsterdamfood #truffle #foodporn #travelblogger

Restaurant Moon in A'dam Toren is open. And we like it. The revolving restaurants makes one round every hour and makes you ooooh and aaaah for the stunning views of Amsterdam. So if you have company that you hate, just take a seat and look outside. But we suggest to go with people you adore, because not only the views are great, the food is too. Jaimie and his team create beautiful and tasteful dishes served in a set 5 or 8 course dinner. They co-create it with a line up of renowned Dutch music artists of which Thomas Acda is the first. Service had some startup problems where after the main course we had seen the 10th waiter at our table. Felt like the service sections didn't move along with the tables. We love La Stage. It has become one of our favorite intimate restaurants in Amsterdam. Great to impress a date with mouth watering dishes, perfect service and even greater wine and food pairings. This restaurant close to the Nieuwmarkt has applied their proof of a Michelin star in the kitchen and doesn't show it off on their front window. It is exemplary for the modesty of the two partnered owners. In working life they divided the jobs clearly: he is in white, she is in black. The whites surprise you with creative and beautiful balanced dishes served in 4- to 6-course a la carte menus, the blacks indulge you with wonderful wines served with passion and knowledge. An empty table is rare, so reservations are advised. Worst WinecafÃ© is a little tucked away in the Barentszstraat near the Haarlemmersquare. They serve fine small dishes for yourself or to share. Their great wine selection is served with passion and know-how. We love it, but it is rare in Amsterdam... We started of with some bread (baked daily at Restaurant As), anchovies with broad beans and pecorino and a clean green salad with mustard dressing. A good start! Tasty and pure.  From the sausage (worst) department we ordered fennel sausage served with braised pepper and fennel and the chicken sausage which came with morels and creamy spinach. We loved the former, liked the latter.  The cosy atmosphere and relaxed setting is perfect for a after work evening or laid back weekend night. The Dutch have handed down the chairmanship of the EU to the Slovakians, which means that the former Marine Land of the Dutch Navy is ours again! Reason for us to explore this extraordinary piece of land adjacent to the Scheepvaartmuseum with its replica of the VOC tall ship 'Amsterdam' at which a beautiful view is granted. The terrace is one of its most pleasant surprises. As is the beer menu. From fresh to the more dark beers, all with a special twist. The combination makes for a great evening on the waterside. That was our first evening. We went back for lunch in the bar. And that was good too. Service was friendly though sometimes a little slow. The sandwiches are tasty and the juices refreshing. And they know how to make a good espresso. Drop by when you are in the hood! We continued to the Scheepskameel. We have a Fish and Chips revival in Amsterdam. ViscafÃ© De Gouden Hoek, close to the Westerpark, was the first offering mainly Fish and Chips from daily catches. We love the ambiance which is very stylish and strengthening the concept. Here is what they do menu wise: some classic startes like croquettes, oysters and crab, but the main focus is of course on fish and chips. You choose one of the daily catches and combine it with one of three crusts with accompanying sauce. Choose from the classic crust with remoulade, a panko-crust with piccalilli or tempura-crust with Japanese Sriracha. When you donâ€™t have enough at hand, daily catches ask for good communication between kitchen and service staff. Which in our case didn't go very well. We were surprised when two out of three dishes served had a totally different fish then the one we had ordered. And we had to find out ourselves. Ah what the heck, the taste was good. Service wasnâ€™t to stable though. Some get it, others donâ€™t. Do we recommend this place? Yup! "Geef mij maar Amsterdam, dat is mooier dan Parijs" - Johnny Jordaan  The Jordaan - traditional home of the dramatic vibrato that is Jordaanlied music and current home of Amsterdam's â€œmost beautiful canal," De Brouwersgracht. A wobbly grid of quiet, narrow streets, the Jordaan is as much Amsterdam heritage as wooden shoes & rain.  On Rozengracht, along the bottom edge of the Jordaan, you'll find Salmuera (@sal_amsterdam) w/ an exceptional mix of cocktails & ceviche. Further down, the terrace at Brandstof (@barbrandstof) is the perfect place to observe one of the great spectacles of Amsterdam â€“ the convergence of pedestrian, bike, scooter, car, taxi, bus, & tram. Who will win?? (SPOILER â€“ It's usually the tram.) Heading north off Rozengracht leads into the Jordaan & over some of the city's prettiest canals. If you get nice light & want to win Instagram, Egelantiersgracht (#egelantiersgracht) & Bloemgracht (#bloemgracht) are great options.  Saturday mornings on Westerstraat, you can either have beers & cigarettes with the locals at De Blaffende Vis (#blaffendevis) or head to the organic market at the Noorderkerk (#noorderkerkmarket). If looking for dinner, De Reiger (#dereiger) has maybe the best ribs in Amsterdam & definitely the coolest restaurant cat. Daalder (#daalder), in a former jazz bar on Lindengracht, also has great food, but unconfirmed if thereâ€™s a restaurant cat.  After dinner (or anytime really), the Jordaan has a solid supply of brown bars. Cafe Thijsen (@cafe_thijssen) & De Tuin (#cafedetuin) are usually fun. But if you're looking for a truly â€œculturalâ€ experience, the fluorescent pink, late-night beacon of Cafe Nol (@cafenolamsterdam) will definitely blow up anything you have to do the next morning.  For more Jordaan suggestions, check out the Sightseen app.  Download #sightseenapp from the App Store. First a short history lesson: Escoffier is seen as the greatest innovator of French cuisine and having learned everything from him, Henri Thijs returned to the Netherlands to open a deli-restaurant combination together with entrepreneur Dikker. This combination was new to the Netherlands and was an instant hit. The succes story is larded with multiple branches, prices, a Michelin star, and the opening of an hotel. Back to here and now. We passed by for lunch and had two of the classic salads. The NiÃ§oise salad came with a severe piece of freshly grilled tuna and other fine ingredients including a poached (we love it poached) egg. The tuna had some natural tough membrane, which made us fillet the fillet. But hey, that happens. We found ingredients of the same quality in our Caesar salad with chicken. Classic and perfectly served. Bread came after we asked for some pieces. Have you guys tried Mojo? It's a delicious Cuban marinade made with lashings of sour orange juice, plenty of cumin, garlic and oregano. If you don't have access to sour oranges, then no problem, use normal fresh orange's and lime juice, to achieve that tart taste. There are many variations of the recipe as there are with many recipes. You can use it on seafood, meats, it's usually used a lot with pork or chicken. Here I've used it on red snapper. If you like garlic and the tart flavours, this one is for you. Recipe on the website soon, go to www.nyamfoodie.com  By the way I'm hosting a pop up at Scrapyard Cafe on Wednesday 8th March. If the pictures on this feed make your mouth water, why don't you come and try some of my food for yourself. We give service an extra star this time! â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸ Moon in A'dam Toren is open. And we like it. The revolving restaurants makes one round every hour and makes you ooooh and aaaah for the stunning views of Amsterdam. So if you have company that you hate, just take a seat and look outside. But we suggest to go with people you adore, because not only the views are great, the food is too. Jaimie and his team create beautiful and tasteful dishes served in a set 5 or 8 course dinner. They co-create it with a line up of renowned Dutch music artists of which Thomas Acda is the first. Service had some startup problems where after the main course we had seen the 10th waiter at our table. Felt like the service sections didn't move along with the tables. The Westerpark hosts several great places to go to for lunch, drinks or an easy dinner. Pacific Parc has gotten some severe nearby competition over the last years (e.g. Mossel & Gin, Brouwerij Troost, Wester Wijnfabriek). These places are run by young, enthusiastic, hospitality minded people. In our multiple visits, we unfortunately didn't get this vibe at Pacific Parc. Aight, so there's this dude who owns a small Japanese restaurant on the top floor of an Asian grocery. It's a one man show. He takes your order and you can see him cook and prepare food right there in front of you. He moves frantically when there are be several people waiting (and that's often the case), but don't worry about the wait for your ramen or pancakes. Take a seat. He will serve you your dish. I went on a Sunday and wanted to go again the next day to try another dish. However, he doesn't work on Mondays and Tuesdays. I was saddened by this fact so I decided that I wanted to tip him because the ramen was delishhh. But he humbly wouldn't accept my tip. Sir, you are an awesome chef. The place is kind of a secret but I'm sure more and more people will find it and it won't be such a secret anymore. Also, his restaurant is only open, at the most, 5 hours each day. I hope to come visit you again and try those pancakes.  #takajapanesekitchen #Amsterdam #amsterdamfood #netherlands #ramen #japanesecuisine #food #foodie #foodporn #yum

Service is a little American, with the 'Hi, my name is Peter and I am your host for tonight', but it is prompt, friendly and spot on! And if you don't want to be wheeled out at the end of your dinner: share it! Saravanaa Bhavan is the new positive surprise in Indian vegetarian delight. Imagine a purple lid ceiling, the ugliest chesterfield chairs available and staff that doesn't know exactly what it serves. But hey, they are friendly. But then add the extensive menu with loads and loads of deliciously prepared dishes and the 75% Indian people that are visiting this restaurant. And when they are here in these big numbers, you know it is good. And they are helpful! Because you next table neighbors know what you should order. Because we couldn't choose, we ordered the Saravanaa Special with all kind of small tries, white rice and papadum. And it was great! Reservations are advised. Restaurant Moon in A'dam Toren is open. And we like it. The revolving restaurants makes one round every hour and makes you ooooh and aaaah for the stunning views of Amsterdam. So if you have company that you hate, just take a seat and look outside. But we suggest to go with people you adore, because not only the views are great, the food is too. Blank canvas... Meringue is always so pretty when it's perfectly white and fluffly! I prefer italian meringue over french meringue for my lemon pies, because I "cook" the eggwhites when incorporating the boiling hot sugar syrup making it more sticky and gooey than the lighter french version. Also italian meringue stays intact for much longer, whereas french meringue becomes runny again quite quickly and doesn't stay good for long. This blank canvas is just dying to get caressed by the flames of a blowtorch and turn into caramelised brown meringue!!!

AMSTERDAM â€¢ There are macaroons, and then there are kokosmakronen - coconut macaroons! We tried some amazing ones found at Noodermarkt.  From @thedutchtable: Dutch have an incredible cookie culture. Grocery stores stock shelves of the most amazing combinations, shapes, ingredients and flavors. Coconut macaroons, or kokosmakronen, are found in a variety of shapes and sizes. Some are small and high, others piped in a circle and flat. Some are yellow (depending on whether you include the egg yolk), others plain white, but the flavor and texture is always moist, coconutty and sweet. Kokosmakronen are usually baked on circles of edible potato starch paper.

AMSTERDAM â€¢ A date with @annabelgreeve at Amsterdam's most famous park - Vondel Park. Top plate is the 'Amsterdam' platter with pate, tartare, cheese. The other plate is bitterballen - a typical meat based Dutch snack with a mixture of beef or veal, flour. A bit like a croquette.

I proudly announce the winner of my #bestveggieburgerofamsterdam competition! My absolute favorite vegetarian burger in Amsterdam is (drumroll please).... the Dutch Weed Burger! ğŸ†  There are so many reasons to like it that I don't know where to start. The patty is one of the few ones that I tried that didn't fell apart. The bun is rich in taste and crispy. The Dutch Weed Burger is fully plant based, so suitable for vegans and great news for our planet. It's also kosher, halal and quite healthy as it contains seaweed and chlorella. And one of the best things about it? It's available at many places throughout the Netherlands, and sometimes even abroad (it'll be in London on October 22nd). I hope that my list inspires you and I'd love to hear your thoughts if you tried one of the veggie burgers on my list!
